if i am weeks pregnant and seeing a doctor when would i call a midwife i want to see the doctor for test of hormone levels and ultrasound but ultimately want a midwife to deliver can i work with both and when should i talk to a midwife asap working with the midwife through the pregnancy and getting to know each other will help you feel more comfortable for a natural birth even if a doctor is doing your pre natal care also midwives often have a limited amount of certain items such as portable birthing tubs for water birth and can only commit to so many births with the same due date they can't be in places at once so you have your best choice of midwife and birthing method if you schedule as early as possible that way she is committed to your birth and if there are scheduling conflicts with other expectant moms in the future your place is secure Obstetrics Midwifery Pregnancy Childbirth Breech birth Breastfeeding Prostate cancer Prenatal care Medicare (Canada) Twin Miscarriage Urinary incontinence Prenatal diagnosis Medicine Abortion Sex assignment Oral contraceptive Hormone replacement therapy (trans) Fertility awareness Endometriosis Androgen insensitivity syndrome Birth control Stomach cancer Menstrual cycle In vitro fertilisation Birth weight Socrates Health insurance Abortion in the United States Turner syndrome National Health Service Caesarean section Stillbirth Spina bifida Physician Medical prescription Nurse Transsexuality Ectopic pregnancy Partial-birth abortion Nursing Guinea pig Intact dilation and extraction Liza of Lambeth Abortion debate Teenage pregnancy Cephalic disorder Tocopherol Multiple birth Human sexual behavior Premature birth Amniotic sac Pregnancy test Tobacco smoking Pregnancy fetishism Gonorrhoea Emergency contraception Natural health Psoriasis Human chorionic gonadotropin EastEnders Abortion in Canada Chemical abortion Gender role Gospel of James Insulin Hypoglycemia Laura Schlessinger Surveillance Friends Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Cytomegal